<p>
<seg id=1> To all of our listeners, now let's take a look at the situation in China. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=2> The Chinese government has again detained several dissidents to prevent members of the Chinese Democratic Party in Zhejiang and Shanghai from holding meetings. </seg>
<seg id=3> Please listen to the report of the Chinese Department of Voice of America, broadcast by Qing Yue. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> According to information from the Chinese Human Rights Democracy Movement Information Center headquartered in Hong Kong, Public Security personnel in Hangzhou removed two members of the Chinese Democratic Party, Zhu Zhengming and Mao Qingxiang, from their homes Friday afternoon. </seg>
<seg id=5> The whereabouts of the two are currently unknown. </seg>
<seg id=6> Prior to that, the police had already detained four other key members of the democracy movement with close ties to the Chinese Democratic Party; their names are:  Yao Zhenxian, Li Guotao, Wu Yilong, and Wang Rongqing. </seg>
<seg id=7> The Chinese Human Rights Democracy Movement Information Center says that about 20 members in various Zhejiang and Shanghai branches of the Chinese Democratic Party were originally planning to hold their first meeting in a restaurant in Hangzhou on Friday afternoon. </seg>
<seg id=8> The police have responded to this meeting with detention. </seg>
<seg id=9> Additionally, public security personnel in various parts of Zhejiang Province have warned other Democracy Movement activists not to leave their homes or they will be detained. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Chinese government views the opposition Chinese Democratic Party as an illegal organization and has detained and interrogated several tens of supporters and activists of this organization. </seg>
<seg id=11> However, in most cases, they have been promptly released. </seg>
<seg id=12> AP, Reuters, and France News Agency have all separately reported the most recent developments released by the Chinese Human Rights Democracy Movement Information Center. </seg>
</p>
